<span id="iii.vi.xii"></span>

<span id="iii.vi.xii-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="iii.vi.xii-p1.1"></span>Chapter XII.—</span>*The Disciples of our
Saviour.*

<span id="iii.vi.xii-p2"></span>1. <span class="c13"><span
id="iii.vi.xii-p2.1"></span>The</span> names of the apostles of our
Saviour are known to every one from the Gospels. <span
id="fr_198"></span>[199](#fn_198.md) But there exists no catalogue of the
seventy disciples. <span id="fr_199"></span>[200](#fn_199.md) Barnabas,
indeed, is said to have been one of them, of whom the Acts of the
apostles makes mention in various places, <span
id="fr_200"></span>[201](#fn_200.md) <span id="page_99">p. 99</span> <span
id="iii.vi.xii-Page_99"></span>and especially Paul in his Epistle to the
Galatians. <span id="fr_201"></span>[202](#fn_201.md)

<span id="iii.vi.xii-p7"></span>2. They say that Sosthenes also, who
wrote to the Corinthians with Paul, was one of them. <span
id="fr_202"></span>[203](#fn_202.md) This is the account of Clement <span
id="fr_203"></span>[204](#fn_203.md) in the fifth book of his Hypotyposes,
in which he also says that Cephas was one of the seventy
disciples, <span id="fr_204"></span>[205](#fn_204.md) a man who bore the
same name as the apostle Peter, and the one concerning whom Paul says,
“When Cephas came to Antioch I withstood him to his face.” <span
id="fr_205"></span>[206](#fn_205.md)

<span id="iii.vi.xii-p12"></span>3. Matthias, <span
id="fr_206"></span>[207](#fn_206.md) also, who was numbered with the
apostles in the place of Judas, and the one who was honored by being
made a candidate with him, <span id="fr_207"></span>[208](#fn_207.md) are
likewise said to have been deemed worthy of the same calling with the
seventy. They say that Thaddeus <span id="fr_208"></span>[209](#fn_208.md)
also was one of them, concerning whom I shall presently relate an
account which has come down to us. <span
id="fr_209"></span>[210](#fn_209.md) And upon examination you will find
that our Saviour had more than seventy disciples, according to the
testimony of Paul, who says that after his resurrection from the dead he
appeared first to Cephas, then to the twelve, and after them to above
five hundred brethren at once, of whom some had fallen asleep; <span
id="fr_210"></span>[211](#fn_210.md) but the majority were still living at
the time he wrote.

<span id="iii.vi.xii-p18"></span>4. Afterwards he says he appeared unto
James, who was one of the so-called brethren of the Saviour. <span
id="fr_211"></span>[212](#fn_211.md) But, since in addition to these, there
were many others who were called apostles, in imitation of the Twelve,
as was Paul himself, he adds: “Afterward he appeared to all the
apostles.” <span id="fr_212"></span>[213](#fn_212.md) So much in regard to
these persons. But the story concerning Thaddeus is as follows.

