trace it back no further than Clement. The Clementine *Recognitions* and
*Homilies* frequently mention Barnabas as an apostle active in
Alexandria and in Rome. One tradition sends him to Milan and makes him
the first bishop of the church there, but the silence of Ambrose in
regard to it is a sufficient proof of its groundlessness. There is
extant an apocryphal work, probably of the fifth century, entitled *Acta
et Passio Barnabæ in Cypro,* which relates his death by martyrdom in
Cyprus. The tradition may be true, but its existence has no weight.
Barnabas came from Cyprus and labored there for at least a time. It
would be natural, therefore, to assign his death (which was necessarily
martyrdom, for no Christian writer of the early centuries could have
admitted that he died a natural death) to that place.

