<span id="iii.vi.xii-p10"></span> Clement is, so far as I know, the
first to make this distinction between Peter the Apostle, and Cephas,
one of the Seventy. The reason for the invention of a second Peter in
the post-apostolic age is easy to understand as resulting from the
desire to do away with the conflict between two apostles. This Cephas
appears frequently in later traditions and is commemorated in the
Menology of Basil on December 9, and in the Armenian calendar on
September 25. In the *Ecclesiastical Canons* he is made one of the
twelve apostles, and distinguished from Peter.

